    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Global Warming and Iraq</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Russ Weiss letter compares Bush administration's response to threat posed by Saddam Hussein's Iraq with its response to threat of global climate change (May 3 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Federal Study Finds Accord on Warming'' (news article, May 3):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Federal Study Finds Accord on Warming'' (news article, May 3):</p>
        <p>It is interesting to contrast the Bush administration's response to the threat posed by Saddam Hussein's Iraq with its response to the threat of global climate change.</p>
        <p>In the former case, the administration publicly highlighted those intelligence fragments that supported its view that Iraq had weapons of mass destruction while discounting any that didn't. In the latter case, the Bush administration has repeatedly countered the general scientific community's warnings about the growing threat posed by global warming by highlighting the reservations of a relatively few iconoclasts.</p>
        <p>In both cases the pattern is the same. Inconvenient truths that dispute the ideological predilections of the Bush administration are pushed aside while sophistries that conform to them are embraced.</p>
        <p>Russ Weiss  Princeton, N.J., May 3, 2006</p>
      </block>
